<h2 id="when-to-use">When to use this pattern</h2>

<p>Use a service unavailable page when your service cannot be used temporarily or permanently.</p>
<p>You might close a service temporarily for:</p>
<ul>
  <li>planned maintenance or upgrades</li>
  <li>unplanned problems which will take time to fix</li>
  <li>reasons outside of your control such as a hosting provider outage</li>
</ul>
<p>If there is an unexpected problem and you can fix it quickly, use the <a href="/design-system/patterns/problem-with-this-service-page">There is a problem with this service page</a>. If you cannot fix the problem quickly, use this service unavailable pattern. "Quickly" means different things for different services, but for example, within an hour.</p> 
<p>Have a general page in case you need to make a service unavailable quickly and do not have time to update the page. As soon as you know when the service will be available, update the page and let users know.</p>
<p>Consider what users should do while the service is unavailable. For example, include a phone number they can contact for urgent issues or a link to a form they can download to record information temporarily.</p>
<p>There are different versions of this pattern:</p>
<ul>
  <li><a href="#general-page">general page</a></li>
  <li><a href="#when-you-know-when-service-will-be-available">when you know when the service will be available</a></li>
  <li><a href="#updates">when you have updates about availability</a></li>
  <li><a href="#standalone-page">standalone page</a></li>
  <li><a href="#service-closed-permanently">service closed permanently</a></li>
</ul>

<h2 id="how-to-use">How to use this pattern</h2>
<p>The page should include:</p>
<ul> 
  <li>"Sorry, this service is unavailable – service name – NHS" as the page title</li>
  <li>"Sorry, this service is unavailable" as the <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code></li>
  <li>the day, date and time it is going to be available or what to do if it is permanently closed</li>
  <li>an alternative journey, for users on a transactional service</li>
  <li>contact information, if it helps meet a user need</li>
</ul>
<p>If your service is a healthcare service, tell users how to complete their task through a different channel.</p>
<p>Contact information should include all numbers and opening times or link to a specific page that includes numbers and opening times. If it's helpful, include "For urgent medical advice" followed by the text "Use <a href="#">111 online</a> or call 111."</p>
<p>If you can:</p>
<ul>
  <li>store previously entered information for a reasonable amount of time so users can resume their journey with re-populated information when the service becomes available again</li>
  <li>tell the user what has happened to their answers if they're in the middle of a transaction</li>
</ul>
<p>Do not ask users to report errors unless you know that this meets a user need.</p>
<p>Have clear and concise content and do not use:</p>
<ul>
  <li>breadcrumbs or a back button</li>
  <li>vague, unhelpful words like "maintenance", "improvements"</li>
  <li>red text to warn people</li>
  <li>too many links</li>
</ul>

